image.altText: statue wrapped in black plastic and cordoned off by fencing

props.synopsis: Vandals have decapitated the bronze statues of two prime ministers in Ballarat in the lead-up to Australia Day.

title.children: Prime ministers' busts decapitated in Ballarat Botanical Gardens

image.altText: Three police officers in dark uniforms and yellow vests that say police stand on a dark street corner beside police tape.

props.synopsis: Police are searching for an offender who shot at a group of youths in Collingwood, seriously injuring two boys.

title.children: Two teenagers in serious condition after shooting in inner Melbourne

image.altText: The PM with a face mask

props.synopsis: It's been about five years since the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed in Australia. This is what Australia living through "unprecedented times" looks like in numbers.

title.children: COVID-19 hit Australia five years ago. These numbers show its impact

image.altText: A man cleans an elephant foot through a metal cage.

props.synopsis: Moving home is always stressful. But for Melbourne's much-loved elephants, a shift to Werribee promises to help the herd grow and thrive.

title.children: Keepers hope tragedy at Melbourne Zoo can save the rest of the herd

image.altText: A close up of Anthony Albanese in a suit.

props.synopsis: Anthony Albanese points to the array of measures his government has taken to tackle the scourge of anti-Semitism. But he can't escape the impression of seeming perennially on the back foot and often lacking adequate empathy and sensitivity in dealing with the issue.

title.children: Albanese struggles to strike the right note on anti-Semitism

image.altText: A young Aboriginal girl is doing ballet wearing traditional clothes. She is wearing brown emu feathers and is painted in ochre

props.synopsis: Australia Day brings up mixed emotions and opinions for many people. Despite this, there is a growth in First Nations cultural festivals being held on the day and this is why.

title.children: There is a growth in First Nations cultural on January 26. This is why

image.altText: A truck and the mangled ruins of other vehicles next to a country highway.

props.synopsis: Melbourne man Christopher Joannidis, 30, was pulled over by police moments before causing the fatal pile-up in northern Victoria in 2023.

title.children: Jail for Mercedes driver who caused five deaths while on way to wedding

image.altText: Composite image of Madison Keys, Novak Djokovic and Paula Badosa at the Australian Open.

props.synopsis: Aryna Sabalenka offers a shopping trip to buy back a friendship, an umpire gets caught singing during a set break and identical twins make it look like you're seeing double. Here are the quick hits from day 12 of the Australian Open.

title.children: Five quick hits: Shopping trip bribe and umpire sets up singing career

image.altText: A man and woman holding a photo of a woman

props.synopsis: The Victorian coroner has indicated he will not hold a public inquest into the death of Caitlin Wainrib, but acknowledges there are more questions than answers over her death.

title.children: Public inquest unlikely despite Melbourne family's fears of foul play

image.altText: A man with stubble and grey hair films a video on social media.

props.synopsis: Brian Barnes has been charged with murder after the death of Merril Kelly in the regional town of Quambatook.

title.children: Alleged murder victim named as accused killer faces Victorian court

image.altText: A pair of police officers walk on either side of a man in a hoodie.

props.synopsis: A Melbourne man has been charged in connection with a threat to destroy a tobacco store that was later set alight in regional Victoria 18 months ago.

title.children: Man arrested over threat to torch tobacco shop that was later set alight

image.altText: Protesters fill the intersection in front of Flinders Street Station.

props.synopsis: Organisers of Melbourne's Invasion Day rally say they have no plans to disrupt the Australian Open, and misinformation suggesting they did has caused "harm and distress".

title.children: Melbourne Invasion Day march organisers dispel misinformation over CBD route

image.altText: Blue police tape near crime scene

props.synopsis: Nine people have been charged over their involvement in anti-Semitic attacks in Sydney, but none have been charged with terrorism. Researchers say it's harder to meet that threshold.

title.children: Why have Sydney's anti-Semitic attacks not been labelled terrorism?

image.altText: A person wearing a navy police uniform and cap waves a pride flag while another has a rainbow fan.

props.synopsis: Organisers say they've banned any group from wearing official uniforms as they try to ensure vulnerable communities feel safe.

title.children: Police to no longer march in Midsumma LGBTIQA+ parade after uniform ban

image.altText: Baby Penguin sitting in a burrow

props.synopsis: A sudden drop in adult little penguin numbers at Bicheno on Tasmania's east coast has led to alarm for the fate of the colony as penguin chicks reliant on parents are seen dying.

title.children: Chicks starving as little penguins fail to return from warming seas

image.altText: A happy elderly woman smiling in an outdoor swimming pool

props.synopsis: Joy Davis learnt to swim at eight, later dived for thrills into an old quarry, and while mayor, opened Portland's town pool in 1977. She is still swimming laps to stay active.

title.children: With the motto 'just hop in and do it', this 96yo swims five days a week

image.altText: Madison Keys celebrates winning her Australian Open semifinal.

props.synopsis: Madison Keys saves a match point on her way to defeating Iga Świątek in the Australian Open semifinals, booking a berth in the tournament decider.

title.children: How a 'heartbreaking' loss inspired Keys's thrilling upset of Świątek

image.altText: Aryna Sabalenka celebrates a point against Paula Badosa

props.synopsis: Aryna Sabalenka has put herself within reach of a third-straight Australian Open title after storming through the semifinals.

title.children: Sabalenka vows to 'pay for whatever' opponent wants after semifinal win

image.altText: Ben Shelton speaks into a microphone during an Australian Open interview.

props.synopsis: After booking his maiden Australian Open semifinal spot, Ben Shelton took it upon himself to take aim at tennis broadcasters and on-court interviewers over their line of questioning to players.

title.children: Shelton joins Djokovic in calling out Aus Open broadcasters over 'negativity'

image.altText: Hadi Nazari places a thumbs up while in a helicopter.

props.synopsis: Hadi Nazari told the hikers who found him after two weeks missing in the NSW bush that he used journal entries in a logbook inside a mountain hut to plan his route to safety.

title.children: Logbooks found in remote hut helped hiker Hadi Nazari find rescuers

image.altText: Strip of suburban homes on street, grey houses, blue skies, scattered clouds.

title.children: Persistence helps home owner avoid insurance 'loyalty tax'

image.altText: Cars queue up on an exit road.

props.synopsis: The $333.5 million investment between the Allan and Albanese governments will upgrade the Werribee Main Road — Princes Freeway Interchange and the Ballan Road Intersection.

title.children: One of Melbourne's most dangerous intersections set for major upgrade

image.altText: A birds-eye photograph of the front of a house, with a road and the police cards around it. A body has been blurred.

props.synopsis: Police said neighbours managed to pull a man from the Deer Park house but were unable to revive him. The fire was contained to a bedroom.

title.children: One dead in house fire in Melbourne's west

image.altText: Margo Neas is relieved to have her cat home with her in Melbourne.

props.synopsis: Mittens, 8, was booked for one-way travel with her family from Christchurch to their new home in Melbourne.

title.children: Cat forgotten in plane cargo hold reunited with Melbourne family

image.altText: George Brandis speaks to reporters in Canberra

props.synopsis: George Brandis, who is now a professor of national security at the Australian National University, says Australia's hate crime laws and their penalties are not strong enough.

title.children: Former attorney-general backs beefing up of Australia's hate crime laws

image.altText: A cartoon cat.

props.synopsis: Before Mickey Mouse, Felix the Cat was the biggest thing in animation. But behind the success of the cartoon cat, his creator lived a controversial and tragic life.

title.children: Felix the Cat shone on screen — but his creator had dark secrets

image.altText: A bald man sits alone at a long table with a microphone. He is wearing a black suit, white collared shirt and purple tie.

props.synopsis: Carlton Football Club president Luke Sayers says a lewd photo was posted to his social media after it was compromised, and he will step down immediately.

title.children: Carlton president steps down, as AFL inquiry finds he did not breach rules

image.altText: A big red-brown rock in front of a cloudy sky.

props.synopsis: Traditional owners in western Victoria say a draft management plan for Mt Arapiles-Tooan State Park has re-ignited racial abuse and harassment of Aboriginal people online and in the community.

title.children: Aboriginal people say Mt Arapiles climbing ban has sparked racist backlash

image.altText: A large sign and crest on a wall saying, Melbourne Magistrates' Court

props.synopsis: A Victorian stalker who tormented two women has been jailed, with a magistrate describing his offending as "a relentless and protracted campaign of abuse".

title.children: Victorian stalker jailed over 'campaign of abuse' against women

image.altText: Anmol wearing a purple suit.

props.synopsis: Anmol Bajwa, 36, has been remembered by family and friends as a "loving" and "inspiring" father.

title.children: Outpouring of grief after father found dead near Melbourne playground

image.altText: Nurse about to prick person in finger to test for bacteria

props.synopsis: Does your infection require antibiotics? Two tests are being trialled to remove the guesswork for GPs and confirm whether a test is bacterial or viral almost instantly.

title.children: New tests aim to ease diagnosis for GPs and reduce antibiotic use

image.altText: woman with dark rimmed glasses who is age 37 looking at her laptop

props.synopsis: When Nicole Sherwin lost her job, she found fiscal inspiration in unique places. She has saved a bunch, but not everyone is convinced she found it at the best source.

title.children: Mum saved $350 a month after losing her job

image.altText: Suzie Blade is wearing a pink jumper and foam rolling a set of pantry drawers.

props.synopsis: A facility in Melbourne's hospital precinct is boosting wellbeing for cancer patients and their loved ones, over cups of coffee and important conversations.

title.children: As she sat at Christmas lunch, Suzie was carrying a heavy secret

image.altText: The exterior of a small building.

props.synopsis: Police still do not know what caused the death of Rachael Dixon at a health retreat in Central Victoria last year, but have charged a 53-year-old woman involved in the retreat with drug trafficking.

image.altText: A woman cries in front of a car.

props.synopsis: Two leading lawyers and a juror reveal what goes on behind the scenes of a high-profile murder trial, as Victoria's Supreme Court prepares for the Erin Patterson triple-murder case later this year.

title.children: Lawyers, juror reveal what goes on behind the scenes of a murder trial
